<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="442" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,188,213]" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[470,632,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planivertex">
<emphasis box="[470,632,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">C. planivertex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the conspicuously flattened part of the head posterior to the ocellar triangle, especially the vertex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="442" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,260,285]" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[348,511,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planivertex">
<emphasis box="[348,511,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">C. planivertex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[673,836,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeruginosa">
<emphasis box="[673,836,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">C. aeruginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it can be distinguished by its striking yellow/brownish coloration. Also, while males present a very unusual phallic bulb (slightly elongated and unusually cylindrical), females have conspicuously cylindrical and thin paired spermathecae, differing from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[215,382,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="442" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[215,382,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="442">Cardiacephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
